description.text:
This thing improved my prints and enabled me to print on the whole bed, where a print would use the whole surface. Can't stress the fact big enough about how easy it is with this way of leveling the bed. These cheap Harbor Freight Dial Indicators are THE ticket to quick, easy, and better than any way yet i've found.  
This fits the harbor freight analog dial indicator 1 inch travel. The barrel is 3/8th inches at the top and is 7/8 inches of the barrel down and then the plunger goes further down from there. Will get the part number on it and update it on here later.  
If you spent what you did for all that you need to build or buy a 3D printer and skimp on the cheap side on a 10 buck item that will remove some of the most hardest to find and fix problems on getting good prints, then your selling your printer way to short.   
A good level bed will make prints that stick to the bed so much easyer. Also keep you from having to squssh the first layer to the point where you can get much better fine prints without as much scraping and finishing after prints.  
I did not have any magnets and after studying how to best do this tool with out them, i realized how heavy these dial indicators are. They are heavy enough to push the springed plunger down and set fine with out the magnets. I set mine on the X-axis and grab the front rod and indicator bracket and pivot the indicator up and down a few times to get a nice reading and adjust from there. It seems to do much better that way. No need for magnets, maybe better.  
If you have a bed that springs out with the spring of these indicators, you got bigger problems than your bed out of level. Believe me these cheap, yet great little indicators have such a light spring in them that a good bed setup should not budge holding the pressure of them. Like i said the weight of the indicator will push itself down the whole 1 inch of travel.  
I don't think people realize that the bed has to be in nearest perfect alignment with the X-rods. (the rods the extruder rides on) With this task and the dial indicator, it is easy to do.  
1) Move the bed as far forward as to let the indicator tip set about a quarter inch inward toward the middle from the bed support screw. Start with the right back bed support screw and then move over to the left back support screw.  
2) Remember that the left and right threaded rods play a huge part in the bed running parallel to the X-axis. So get the bed level best you can, but a large movement can be done by just dropping or lifting the X-axis with the threaded rods. Any way you can get the back of the bed running parallel with the X-axis you have to do it.  
3) Next move the bed as to do the same on the front two bed support screws. But Do Not Touch The Threaded Rods Adjustment, leave them where you set the back at and adjust only the front bed support screws.  
4) Now you have the best level bed you have ever had, a near guarantee. Just don't forget to calibrate the bed for printing with the calibration script in SF.   
Hope you enjoy this tool as much as i did, want need it again until i do something to knock it out. Well worth the print time.

description.text:
I had an entire thing typed up, but since I took too long to submit, I got a 404. Thanks, makerbot.

This is a continuation of the Kuuga helmet I posted earlier-made it for my cosplay. It's most of the major pieces you'd need for the suit, minus the chest armor (which isn't a good idea to print in the first place. Just use EVA foam for that). Not everything is scaled, and you'll need to slice the scythes into multiple parts via meshmixer or something like that to print them.

There's also a blend file with the raw wireframes if you want to play with that (filename: A Mess); they were all speedmodeled, so there are probably errors. Feel free to use it for pepakura and whatnot.

Update, 1/26/18: Added legscythe modified. It's more scaled to a proportional human body, and should sit flush with your leg without scaling if your calf is around 31 cm in circumference. Legscythe (regular) probably won't be flush with your leg unless you're ridiculously beefy.

Printed in flexible PLA (shoulderpads) and TPU (everything else). Finished via lots of bondo (shoulderpads and other low-flex areas) and kinda ridiculous amounts of modge podge (did you know if you cake enough of it on and have 200 grit sandpaper you can sand modge podge? wild).

These are all attached to my body via magnets. I have a couple pieces of knitted elastic sitting underneath the suit which have neodymium magnets glued onto them. I use both smaller ones (the 10-pack from Harbor Freight, maybe 5/16 in/8mm in diameter) and larger ones (.5 in/13mm diameter). 2 'sets' (4 magnets total per scythe) work fairly well for the arms, but will occasionally still fall off. Haven't tried the legs yet.

crying 2 and weeks before otakon. don't do ultimate form as a first suit. learn from my mistakes.

Otherwise: Blender, basic wireframe and a subdivision surface modifier with edge creases. These are all taken from the new figuart; I used it as reference for the basic shapes and dimensions via calipers. If you want to screw around with the wireframes, they're all in the .blend file.

Printed the grey part using flex filament (TPU). It won't work on PLA or ABS, since it need to fit inside the GoPro case.

Must use 4 x M2x8mm bolts - or hot-glue the two parts and use a blowdrier to change the filter when needed.

I had to use supports to print the flex part, but that maybe because my printer sucks printing flex overhangs. 10% infill on both parts.

SuperView mode can capture the lens frame. Use a narrow capture angle (wide) or crop a little.
I'll try latter to bring the filter closer and make the frame thinner.

description.text:
UPDATE:
I made a new frontplate to support a 12v 40mm LED ring, with a cover.
(C270_WideLens_FrontPlate_LED and C270_WideLens_LED_Cover)

I changed all the parts for the C270 camera mount, and made it support a cheap wide angle lens.
-It will require an extra M3 screw (plus a washer if the head is small) for attaching the camera to the arm, and an M4 screw to be able to adjust the vertical camera angle.

-The frontplate and backplate will require two ~m2.5x12 screws (Notune21 hasn't specified, so this is just a guesstimate). But I used two small m3 wood screws I had laying around, and they seem to have worked just fine.

I found the original design hard to keep aimed and the extruder assembly kept bumping into the camera during auto calibration.

-The arm has been modified to fit the MK2S buildplate, shortened and made in one piece (removing the need for the printed plastic screw). I also added two slots on the back for zip ties.

-The mount that screws directly into the camera has had the groove removed.

-The camera parts (back plate, front plate and focus ring) have been modified to support a wide angle lens.

I used a cheap magnetic lens made for cellphones.

description.text:
Most older Sears Craftsman radial arm saws had a rubber 90 degree sawdust exhaust port on the front of the saw, which directed sawdust to the left of the operator. This rubber exhaust port was frequently damaged or lost, which resulted in sawdust being shot directly into the chest and face of the operator. This adapter does two things. First, it directs the sawdust stream through a 180 degree path, so that the sawdust is directed away from the operator. Secondly, it provides a friction coupling to most standard craftsman shop vacuums, so that sawdust generated during saw usage is automatically vacuumed up. This makes cleanup easier, and results in less airborne sawdust (airborne sawdust poses a respiratory risk).

Using this adapter requires a small modification to the saw exhaust port, which I achieved using a dremel tool and a diamond cutting bit (see photograph). Also, because the casting process results in small differences in sizes, it may be necessary to scale the model up or down slightly in order to achieve a perfect fit. I recommend that you create a quick, low res model first, to verify sizing. I built my model using white ABS, on a heated bed using a 5mm skirt.

Update: The 67mm wheel uses 4mm bolts throughout. I also widened the hub, increased the size of the rollers and improved the threaded hub insert for both wheel sizes.

I recommend printing the 67mm wheel prior to trying the smaller wheel. It would be great to see what would be capable with a SLA/DLP resin type printer. I envisage some neat variants of the main body to reduce material usage.

In the works is a two part roller that can be printed in two materials ( eg. plastic and ninja flex) in order to produce a solid roller body with an outer that would have greater grip. I have removed the "work in progress" tag, though more updates will come :)

These are omnidirectional wheels produced for robotics projects. They are designed to have the rollers mounted via M4 x 40mm bolts and the hub has been produced so that different shafts can be accommodated while not changing the overall design.

These are a work in progress, and are still being optimised for FDM printing. They are currently suitable for high-res FDM/FFM type printers and SLS/SLA/SLM/DLP type printers. Ideally I would like to have these work well while printing on a standard FDM/FFM printer operated by a user with minimal skills.

The provided model is compatible with http://www.dagurobot.com type motor/gearbox shafts e.g. http://www.dagurobot.com/goods.php?id=165

If you use this model, please do like/share/comment and let me know how you go with it. I am interested to see some printed parts from the 3D printing and robotics community.

If you would like advice on how to make a centre hub to suit a particular shaft, drop me a line and we can discuss the possibilities. It does not take long to modify the hub for another shaft size/arrangement.

title: Jhead Adapter for the Tito Direct Drive Extruder

description.text:
An adapter for the Tito Direct drive Extruder. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:110269. It has been remade to fit a Jhead, but I needed the extra clearance as I am mounting two of these face to face on my Prusa V2. The clearance is needed for the belt. I did have to drill out my x carriage to match this hole pattern and allow for two hot ends to be put back to back. The issues I have seen with mounting these in this manner are:
  • It is hard to feed the filament in during a changeout. I have compensated by releasing tension on the bearing and snipping the filament so that it forms a point.
  • It is hard to get to the MK7 to clean it.

Print and use 2 3mm x 20mm bolts and associated nuts to secure the Jhead.   
Note that the Jhead center point is not the center of the extruder or the adapter, so ensure you have it aligned correctly. The bolt head should be on the same side as the motor.

description.text:
A fully automated inexpensive($50) educational lab experiment to measure optical scattering, in particular polarization and angular cross-section.

On a beginner level the setup is suitable to measure scattering of light by optical gratings. In fact scattering from a CD-R surface is used to calibrate the angular servo control using the well-known equation "grating_constant x sine(nth scattering angle) = n x wavelength".

The experiment was developed in our laboratory physics courses to demonstrate Mie-scattering by microscopic colloidal particles. Mie-scattering refers to light scattering by objects that are comparable to the wavelength. This is typically used in expensive laboratory equipment, to determine size-distributions of colloidal suspensions.

The setup is controlled via an Arduino which fits in the bottom of the device. A small amount of soldering or a separate bread-board is required to assemble the device and should be possible on a undergraduate or even school level.

Detailed information, a list of required components, assembly instructions and software (OpenSCAD files; Arduino Firmware; Python & Octave scripts for analysis of measurements - all GPL licensed) can be found on our dedicated website: http://www.mss.cbi.fau.de/Mie-experiment

A live-demonstration of the measurement can be found here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A-WL2huUDuc

The device was featured in the 3/17 German issue of the Make magazine: https://www.heise.de/make/meldung/Guenstig-dank-Maker-Technik-Optik-Experiment-fuer-Schulen-und-Unis-3716721.html

For details on the experiment and explanation of the physics of Mie-scattering we published a scientific paper here:

C. Scholz, A. Sack, M. Heckel and T. Pöschel, Inexpensive Mie scattering experiment for the classroom manufactured by 3D printing, Eur. J. Phys. 37 055305 (2016)
http://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/0143-0807/37/5/055305

All parts were printed using an FDM printer (Kühling & Kühling RepRap), PLA or ABS material with 20% filling and 80% for the base. Post-processing involves gluing and screwing together the individual parts and electronic components. Some minor adjustments might be needed to the components (servos, diodes, etc) that are available to you.

title: Stacking Planter Pods #2, vertical garden, 6-gang per level

description.text:
More than two years in the making, this is the second version of my original concept for a stacking, nesting modular herb-garden planter!

Inspired by the structure of a pinecone, this version is more advanced than my first design in this series because it does not require tongue and groove to hold the device together. This version uses an inward-sloping helical structure which draws the pods towards the center.

The key advantage here is two-fold, no unsightly shapes can be seen used to hold the parts together, as in the first design, and far more importantly, any individual pod can be taken out of the structure and replaced at will!

You can take a pod out, move it around, exchange it for another pod, without having to remove the pods above and around it, as you would need to in the first design iteration.

This also more closely mimics the structure of a pinecone as well.

I hope you are as excited about this idea as I am; I can easily see people building little herb or flower-gardens in their kitchen windows, mounting these on lazy-susans that let them rotate the whole garden and choose which herbs get the most sun, or even take advantage of the center-hole to mount them on a pole or hang them from the roof.

These nesting planter pods let you grow any number of garden herbs, flowers, or succulents, and mix or match them as desired.

The individual pods aren't much more than 4" in any one direction, and should be printable by most 3D printers. As for the height, it's only limited by how many you want to print, though very tall versions should consider using a stick or wire-rope down the center to keep it from toppling over.

If you put a stick through the center, integrated water-holes allow the pods to be individually-watered, and allow the excess water to drain into the center of the planter and down to the bottom nicely, even if you place a large rod down the middle.

The footer sections have tongue-and-groove sections used to hold the pods together. With about .010" extra space overall, so that even if your printer isn't great at holding good tolerances it should work decently fine.

The center-hole is larger than in the previous design, and could allow you to run a drip system through the middle and up through the drainage-hole if you chose.

And, as always, my designs are completely open-source, public-domain dedicated. Feel free to alter in any way you like, even to commercialize them immediately. In fact, if I don't see these for sale in Home Depot by the end of the year, I will be disappointed :P

Some additional thoughts:

  • The wall-thickness modeled is .100".

  • The walls need to be water tight. It may help to use some secondary process to make the pods water-tight if your print fails to produce a water-tight product. Hot-wax perhaps? Or pitch? Some have had good results with simple Elmer's wood glue.

  • In the images of the assembly, I've colored one of the pods blue so it is easy to see how an individual pod is part of the larger whole.

  • The footer parts and the top parts were made from the same stacking-pod model as the pods themselves, modified for that position. They are not optional to use as they are required to hold the pods together. So the entire assembly is constructed from three-separate model variants of one pod. The header-pods on top ARE optional.

  • It could be made into a hanging-planter by passing a wire or string through the center of a piece of wood dowel and tying off a knot.

  • It is advisable to put a dish of some sort under the bottom to catch excess water, if used indoors.

  • Footer sections have new drainage holes for water.

description.text:
Quiet as a mouse!

My Prusa MK2 printer is great but boy was it loud, in power mode the kitchen table telegraphed the sound of the stepper motors to the far reaches of the house so much that people all through the house couldn't sleep over night.

However, I had a set of 4 matching springs tangling up the spring stash (doesn't everyone have one of those?) and once I found them it didn't take long to squirrel this design out- it's so quiet now that I'm still surprised when it starts printing....

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15 optimised

Infill:

default

Notes:

no muss no fuss

Intent and Execution:

The L-bracket has a hole to fit the included pin of the same diameter (sized in Rhino3D to fit my found springs via the .3dm file)- I found this to make a nice interference fit when pressed in a small desktop vice, I'm sure a C-clamp would do just as well. Resize the pin/hole combo to fit whatever springs you have laying around, I did a few test pins to check the fit. I sized their length so that they would fit when pressed beyond the upper surface by the thickness of the L-bracket of another of the freshly minted units.

It seems like perhaps two thirds of the weight is on the back 2 feet, so if you have six springs available then take the opportunity to double them up in the back by printing 6 copies and using pairs back to back in the rear. I have mine pictured singly as I only had 4 springs, if I print an extra set I'll update the pics.

You can see how the prongs in the L-bracket fit around the threaded rods via the pics. I used some of the zillions of extra zip ties that came with the printer to strap the L brackets on. The pres-fit pin protrudes up just the right amount to touch off on the felt pad using the back of another L-bracket to space (3mm if I recall, could have been 4). I felt better about not using glue with the pin going all the way through like that and there is still plenty to grab the spring- too long and you loose travel and too short you loose grip.

Because the spring end wraps are not ground flush the bottom the springs kick off a bit from perpendicular to the table. This hasn't been a problem for me but if you are feeling nitpicky about it then either grind the ends of the springs square or make a nice little pocket for the end of the spring in the foot via CAD- have fun with that last one, as mismatching the ramp will be just as bad as no change at all except for the wasted time. If you do grind the spring go very light and keep everything wet all the time or you will loose the temper wherever you overheated it. Just glueing them on while they are unloaded and pointing straight is probably the most rational thing to do.

Once on the springs the printer bobbles like a bantamweight boxer at times but the quality has been completely unaffected thus far, if anything the net acceleration/decelleration has been decreased without having to touch the speed settings. I had two springs that were lighter than the other 4 so I put them under the corners of the aluminum frame to lessen the bobble, I may print another pair of parts to add them back-to-back with the existing ones in the rear of the unit.

Of course I had to size the feet to fit typical 1" stick-on furniture felts.

p.s.
A last tip, on the side that has two linear bearings on the Y axis don't let the zip ties interfere with their progress into the recess or you will scare the daylights out of yourself when the bearings bump into them and the steppers groan because the table can't touch the limit switch. I cut mine and repositioned them from where they are in the pictures on that side, lots of prints later still no problems since.

So today, I bought a Milwaukee m12 drill kit from Home Depot. There was a special promotion, buy the $129 drill kill, get a two pack of batteries free. I figured there'd be 3 bats total, but the kit itself had two. So, I've got one battery in the drill and 3 spares. So, I took the end cap and made a 3 battery holder. I printed this at 101% of size in S3D and it is a perfect fit for the batteries. (100% being the size of the original cap - but I've always had tight fitting things when printed at 100%. It's probably my printer - but I'd recommend 101.5% if I were to do it again.) I'm also using a 0.3mm nozzle, so if you're still using 0.4mm nozzle you might just want to increase it to 102%. I'd say if you print with a flex material (tpu) then 100% is fine.

I used red pla at 210c. No supports. Printed good the first time. There is a small hole in the back for if you want to hang the mount on a wall or something.

title: Anet A8 30A uprated PSU (50x150mm centres) IEC Switch mount and cover

description.text:
Simple Switched IEC Socket and cover for PSU

This is a basic cover to go round the connectors on the bottom of an uprated 30A PSU for the Anet A8. These PSUs are cheap and readily available on Amazon, eBay and other places. Most have M4 mounting holes on the back at 50mm (W) and 150mm (H) centres so require some new holes to be drilled in the Anet frame; which is pretty straightforward.

This cover holds a switched and fused IEC mains socket for a normal "kettle lead". It also has a small compartment which I am using to hold a buck converter on a small piece of vero board which I am using to supply 5v DC to a Raspberry Pi Zero W which I mounted near the main board; this lets me run Octoprint etc.

The design file is included in OpenSCAD. You can easily change the measurements to suit your exact PSU and you will almost certainly want to adjust the height of the PSU from the base as this will be entirely dependent on where you drilled the new mounting holes for the PSU.

The slot on the left hand side (as you look at the front) is for the Z2 stepper cable and the hole toward the top "pops" over the Button head of one of the Anet A8 frame screws to locate the left side nice and firmly. The right side has a hole to match up with an M4 screw hole in the side of the PSU. For this I used a short M4 screw, e.g. ~5mm.

You'll need to print a Holder and Holder w/ Nut as well as two of whichever clamp you need. The clamps have identifying marks on them to help keep them in order.

The 60mm Flying Base and 60mm Round base require different clamps as the 60mm Round base is actually 64mm in diameter.

35mm M3 round head machine screw
M3 nut
16mm / 5/8" Marble
4 x #6 x 1/2 wood screw (M3.5 x 12)
2 pieces of rubber (either rubber splicing tape or bits of rubber band)

The "Screw Hole Template" is there if you want to make your own fittings for this item. Don't print it, use it as cutting tool when making your 3D models to get the hole spacing correct easily.

I'll add more base sizes once I can get accurate measurements - quite a few of the bases are not actually the sizes they are listed as.

description.text:
Missile Turret

This is a missile turret for 28mm wargaming, to make either a heavy support tank or fortification terrain. If assembled and painted carefully, the missile bays rotate on the supporting arm. There are pockets built into the design to optionally magnetize the end caps in order to switch between high explosive and wide area missiles. The base pedestal plug is 25mm, compatible with Games Workshop's Rhino-chassis hatches. Games Workshop's Rhino model shown in photos only to demonstrate scale.

Components

The missile end caps can either be glued on or magnetized. To magnetize them you'll need:

  • 4x 1/8” steel ball bearings for the body, e.g., K&J Magnetics' NSB2
  • 8x 1/8” by 1/16” disc magnets for the missile end caps, e.g., K&J Magnetics' D21

Printing

The pieces have been designed to not require any supports, with only very modest bridging and overhang capabilities required. They should be printed as oriented in the STLs: Missile end caps laying flat, and the arm cap upside down. See the photo in the gallery for an example layout in Cura.

Assembly

Dry fit everything before gluing to make sure it fits!

  1. Glue the plug into the bottom of the base
  2. Put a dab of glue in the three-sided pockets on the tops of the base arms, being careful to keep the glue away from the cylindrical cut where the body goes. Rest the body in the arm, then drop the cap into place on the top of the arm and hold it while the glue sets.
  3. Test that the magnets and ball bearings all sit perfectly flush to the surface! If they don't, hand drill or scrape out the pocket until they do.
  4. Put a dab of glue in each pocket on the body and then drop in the ball bearings.
  5. Put a dab of glue in each pocket on the missile caps and then slide in
    the magnets.

All done!

title: Alternate D-Bot Power Supply Mount and Endcap
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
For a few reasons, I wanted to move my power supply to a side rail on my D-Bot printer, and I feel its pretty unsafe to have a power supply with exposed mains terminals, especially on a metal-frame printer.

These parts do two things, which can obviously be used together or separately. First, this is a set of mounting clips that work the same as the "stock" power supply mounts on the D-Bot, but raise the power supply an additional 13mm, which allows it to be mounted above the brackets screwed to the side rail.

Secondly, this includes an end-cap that mounts to the stock power supply, with a mounting hole for the stock switch. This has the safety benefit of keeping all the high-voltage inside the enclosure, where its less likely to be accidentally touched.

Two versions of the end cap are uploaded here. The first is just that -- the endcap for the switch. The second has an additional opening that can be used with the uploaded spacer ring to add a 12v dual USB port running off the power supply. (Using this part: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01HPSY4RY) This reduces the need for additional USB wall warts if you're running OctoPi or USB powered web cameras, etc.

You'll need some short M4 screws to attach the endcap, and the side brackets need 38mm M4 screws.

title: Dingoboy's Folgertech FT-5 Overhead Spool Holder

description.text:
Similar to some other FT-5 spool mounts, but with a couple of differences:

  1. I designed a horizontal lip to hold the weight, rather than relying on the bolts & T-nuts to support all of the weight.

  2. Chose to design this one to work with a 1" standard PVC pipe. (That's 1" ID, 36mm outer diameter) PVC pipes are light & they are usually cheaper to buy & easier to cut than metal rods.

  3. Completely optional: I designed 2 different ring clamps to hold the pipe itself in place on the brackets & to hold the spool in place on the pipe.

All you NEED to print for this is the pair of brackets. They are designed to mount with the same M5x10mm bolts & M5 T-nuts that the FT-5 melamine parts mount with. I designed 5 mounting holes on the side of the bracket & 5 on the horizontal lip. I chose to use the horizontal lip, and found that 3 bolts were plenty. Brackets are firmly held in place.

The ring clamps can be used to hold the pipe on the brackets, and to hold the spool in place on the pipe.

I didn't want the pipe to vibrate off the brackets while printing. So I desgned the set-screw type rings to hold it firmly in place. You can use one on each end, 2 on each end, whatever works for you. I put 2 on one end, leaving a gap around the bracet, so I can tilt the pipe up from theo ther end without snapping anything. Ths left the other end open for easy spool swaps. The set-screw clamps each have 3 holes & nut traps to give you options: M3, M4, or M5 bolts and nuts can be used. Just press the nut into the appropritately sized trap with pliers. ***DO NOT USE NYLOCK NUTS- they are too tall, and they will not let the clamp fit onto the PVC.

If, like me, you want your spool to stay in place during printing, I would print 2 of the spring clamps & slide them into place around the spool. They take a little force to slide onto the end of the pipe, since they are purposely undersized to provide the spring pressure. You can easily lift the spool over them to remove & replace, but they will slide by hand as well to accomodate different widths of spools.

description.text: I searched for an LED lit heart as a Valentine's Day gift, but couldn't find exactly what I wanted. I wanted a subtle animation and a template which could be customized. I set out to make this based on Adafruit's NeoPixels and Adafruit's Trinket. http://youtu.be/lvECzZIMjFc

1) Print out all the pieces except for the stencil. You need to customize that before printing it. When you print it, use a low infill to let more light bleed through, or a higher infill to get a better contrast with your text. You will need 2x brackets. Be sure to print these on their side and you may want to set the infill higher on these for stability. You will need 12x led_clamp models. These (sort of) help secure the LEDs to the main heart. These could use some extra refinements and they are fragile. You will also need:
12 Adafruit NeoPixel LEDs (WS2812). These are the individual leds.
1 Adafruit Trinket
7 screws or nuts&bolts
2-4 2mm screws for the Trinket
24 gauge wire (I used old ATA cables).
USB A to USB mini B. 2) Wire up the LEDs in the main heart. I chose to use two separate channels.
3) Screw or bolt the "back" to the brackets.
4) Screw or bolt the "back" and brackets assembly to the base.
5) Customize the stencil -- use text or whatever as a boolean and subtract that from the stencil. Be creative here!
6) Screw in the Trinket to the base -- you will need to drill pilot holes.
7) Finally, attach the stencil to the main heart and back with 3 screws.
8) Grab the code for the heart here: https://gist.github.com/apetrone/8997116
9) Upload that onto the Trinket and enjoy.

description.text: external 20x20 angle

This is a much more accurate Z endstop!
You'll notice how accurate/stable it is immediately!

Watch it in action:
https://youtu.be/tF2z4EKhI4I

See the video at the time: 3:57 to see the first version I made:
https://youtu.be/JWi-ZnHx8co?t=237

It's very simple just two screws, the lower screw is with flattened end, the upper screw is with sharp end (wood screw). You need to change the endstop logic in the firmware to NC (if it's not NC already).

You will be using two pins only Signal (S) and Negative (-).
DON'T USE THE Positive (+) pin, we don't need the 5 volts.
Before wiring it, adjust the upper screw so it's BARELY touching the lower screw (for the best sensitivity), you can use a multimeter to make sure if it's working as it should.

  • Depends on the bed height from the plat, I provided two parts to chose from (files 1 and 3).
    This is not the final version, it's more to show you the principal.

*The Slower you home Z the more accurate it is (this applies for any Z sensor).

title: GV210 Compact Racing Quad (Uses Falcon 250 Arms)

description.text:
Here we have a 3d printed quad that utilizes widely available Falcon 250 arms to attain durability typically outside that of a printed quad. To assembly you will need...

  • Double sided tape for FC, PDB, FPV cam, HD cam
  • 5mm wide zip ties for antennas/ recording camera (3mm pictured on hd cam, files have 5mm clearance)
  • 8 x M3x10 button head screws for inner arm holes, and top plate.
  • 4 x M3x15(ish) button head screws for outer arm holes/ standoffs
  • Standoffs of your choice, but more low is always more better! I used 5x15mm and that's about as slammed as you'll probably get without an AIO FC.

I built this machine around my electronics, so some considerations...

  • The inner arm holes are NOT FC mounting holes, they aren't meant to line up. Both my PDB and FC have flat bottoms, thus they are both servo taped to the mid/ top plates

  • I'm using a microscopic FPV cam out of an Inductrix FPV

  • The VTX mounting scheme is designed around an FT958

  • The HD cam mount is 36mm wide, so should be great for Foxeer 1/2, Runcam 2, Mobius, YMMV with box style cams.

Definitely post pics if you decide to build one! My AUW with a 1300 4s is 475g which I think is pretty impressive for an HD equipped 5" beast.

Assembly Instruction

Place the bottom of the case by removing the two screws on the left side of the printer. Add the camera in the "camera head". Insert the camera cable through the arm then place the top screw between the arm and the case (the nut has to be on the arm side).
